{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512952","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512952"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:03:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:03:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11981"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11981","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11981"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.07,0.69,0,0.22]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4571"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103194"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4571","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4571"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11981"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85631"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"414"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6855"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6870"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26785"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45076"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103194","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103194"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old woman, presents to her general practitioner seeking advice on screening for breast cancer, and wants to know if she should have a mammogram. She is 12 weeks into a planned pregnancy with her first child. Her general health is good. Prior to her pregnancy, she drank one or two glasses of wine a week, but has stopped drinking since becoming pregnant. She smoked in her early twenties but ceased smoking about seven years ago. Her grandmother died of colorectal cancer when she was 80. There is no family history of breast cancer and she has not noticed any recent changes to her breasts. The physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate advice?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Arrange a screening mammogram","Arrange a screening breast ultrasound","Advise her to become familiar with the normal look and feel of her breasts, and how this may change in pregnancy","Arrange a breast MRI","Reassure her that due to her age and low risk, she will not need any investigations until after she turns 55"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhilst there is a distant family history of colorectal cancer, this is unlikely to increase this patient\u0027s risk of breast cancer. A personal or family history of breast or ovarian cancer, however, contributes to increased risk. There is no family history of breast cancer in this patient and given her age, there is nothing else to suggest the she is at increased risk of breast cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old is at relatively lower risk of breast cancer, however routine population screening begins at 50. Australia runs a \u003Cstrong\u003Ebreast cancer screening program\u003C/strong\u003E through BreastScreen. Women between 50 and 74, who have not had breast cancer, are invited for a free mammogram every two years. Women aged 40 to 49 are not invited but are eligible for a free mammogram on request.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMammograms\u003C/strong\u003E are less reliable in women under 40 due to increased breast density. \u003Cstrong\u003EBreast ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E would be the imaging modality of choice - however given that she is asymptomatic and at low risk, there is no indication for an ultrasound as a screening test. If there were any concerns such as breast lumps or nipple changes however, imaging should be performed, along with biopsy if indicated. \u003Cstrong\u003EBreast MRIs\u003C/strong\u003E can be used in women under age 50 deemed at high risk of breast cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWomen are advised to \u003Cstrong\u003Ebecome generally familiar with the look and feel of their breasts\u003C/strong\u003E, and to see their doctor if they notice any concerning changes. A monthly breast self exam can be helpful and patients should be instructed on the proper technique for self examination. A pregnant woman will almost certainly experience changes to the look and feel of their breasts over the course of their pregnancy and while they breastfeed, so in this case it would be important to advise the patient about what to expect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is recommended that all women, whether or not they undergo mammographic screening, are aware of how their breasts normally look and feel, and promptly report any new or unusual changes (such as a lump, nipple changes, nipple discharge, change in skin colour, skin texture, pain in a breast) to their GP. No one method for women to use when checking their breasts is recommended over another.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Routine breast cancer screening is run through BreastScreen, and available for women 50-74 by invitation and 40-49 on request","Encourage \u0022breast awareness\u0022 and proper self breast examination technique"],"references":["About the BreastScreen Australia Program [Internet]. health.gov.au. 2021 [cited 18 August 2022]. Available from: https://www.health.gov.au/initiatives-and-programs/breastscreen-australia-program/about-the-breastscreen-australia-program","Breast awareness and screening [Internet]. Cancer Council Victoria. [cited 18 August 2022]. Available from: https://www.cancervic.org.au/preventing-cancer/attend-screening/breasts-health/breast-screen","Breast Self-Examination [Internet]. ScienceDirect. 2022 [cited 18 August 2022]. Available from: https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/medicine-and-dentistry/breast-self-examination","Alex A, Bhandary E, McGuire KP. Anatomy and Physiology of the Breast during Pregnancy and Lactation. Adv Exp Med Biol. 2020;1252:3-7. doi: 10.1007/978-3-030-41596-9_1. PMID: 32816256. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32816256/","Guidelines for preventive activities in general practice. 10th edition. RACGP. Breast cancer. \u003Chttps://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/key-racgp-guidelines/view-all-racgp-guidelines/preventive-activities-in-general-practice/cancer/breast-cancer\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85631"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11981"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85631","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85631"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-20T14:50:28+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-20T14:50:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4571"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103194"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"d